            <otmi:snippets>
              <otmi:splitregex>(?-mix:\.\s+(?=[A-Z]))</otmi:splitregex>
              <otmi:snippet>As a student of the renowned German chemist Justus von Liebig, Hofmann had made a name for himself by showing that a basic compound called aniline, obtained from coal tar, had the same properties as a compound distilled from raw, plant-derived indigo</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Boldly, Perkin persuaded his father and brother to set up a small factory with him to manufacture the dye, which he called mauve; the picture here is of a shawl, dyed with mauve, from 1862</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But when the inquisitive Perkin tried the reaction using aniline instead, he got a black precipitate that dissolved in methylated spirits to give a purple solution</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Coal tar was the residue of coal-gas production, and there was intense interest in finding uses for the aromatic compounds, such as aniline, that could be extracted from it</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Hitherto, almost all dyes were natural compounds extracted from plants and animals</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In a classic case of serendipity, Perkin chanced on his famous &quot;aniline mauve&quot; dye while attempting to synthesize something else entirely: quinine, then the only known remedy for malaria</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>One hundred and fifty years ago this week, a teenager experimenting in his makeshift home laboratory made a discovery that in effect launched the modern chemicals industry</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Textiles and dyeing being big business at the time, Perkin was astute enough to test the coloured compound on silk, which it dyed richly</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The Perkins and others (including Hofmann) soon discovered a whole rainbow of aniline dyes, and by the mid-1860s aniline-dye companies included the nascent giants of today&apos;s chemicals industry, such as Bayer, Hoechst and BASF.</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The reaction produced only a reddish sludge</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>William Perkin was an 18-year-old student of August Wilhelm Hofmann at the Royal College of Chemistry in London, working on the chemical synthesis of natural products</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Working at home, Perkin tried to use an aniline derivative to make quinine by oxidation, based on the similarity of their chemical formulae (their molecular structures are very different)</otmi:snippet>
            </otmi:snippets>
